## Overview
A/B Testing is a method used in public and social innovation work to compare two versions of an intervention or product to determine which one performs better based on specific goals.

## Purpose
The purpose of A/B Testing is to provide solid evidence and reliable insights to help identify the most effective solutions and strategies by comparing different variations and measuring user response.

## How it works
To conduct A/B Testing, create two versions of a product or intervention, randomly assign users to each version, set metrics and performance goals, collect performance, usability, and behavioral data, analyze the results, and determine which version achieves the goals more effectively.

## Requirements
A/B Testing requires (1) two distinct versions of an intervention or product, (2) clear and measurable goals, (3) a sufficiently large and diverse sample size, and (4) a platform and mechanism to manage the A/B test and collect data. Basic data analysis skills are also required.

## Reflections
When using A/B Testing, consider starting with a clear hypothesis about what you expect to find, be mindful of external factors that might influence results, and ensure a sufficiently large sample size to achieve reliable results.
